saltOS base-system bootstrap

This directory turns the package recipes under recipes/ into a base root
filesystem for saltOS on a Linux build host. It is an LFS-style staged build
driven entirely by the salt package builder (salt build) and installer
(salt install).

Bootloader choice: GRUB

GRUB is used as the bootloader. saltOS treats full-system rollback as a
first-class feature (DISTRO.md sections 4.2 and 7): every transaction takes a
Btrfs snapshot of the @ subvolume, and the user must be able to boot a previous
deployment from the boot menu. GRUB has mature Btrfs and subvolume support and
can enumerate snapshot subvolumes as bootable deployment entries, which makes
the rollback-from-boot-menu requirement straightforward. systemd-boot was
rejected because it has weaker Btrfs snapshot integration and saltOS does not
use systemd. GRUB is built EFI-only here, targeting x86_64-efi and arm64-efi
selected from SALT_ARCH; efibootmgr/efivar manage the UEFI boot entries.

Stages (build-order.toml)

1. cross-toolchain
   binutils, gcc, the kernel headers (linux), and glibc plus the gcc math
   libraries (gmp, mpfr, mpc). This produces a toolchain capable of building
   the rest of the system for the target arch.

2. temp-tools
   A minimal set of host-independent tools (shell, coreutils, text tools,
   archivers, busybox) built against the new toolchain so the base stage no
   longer depends on the build host's userland.

3. base
   The self-hosting base system: final glibc/gcc/binutils, core libraries
   (zlib, openssl, ncurses, readline, libffi, expat, sqlite, libsodium, ...),
   filesystem and device tooling (e2fsprogs, btrfs-progs, eudev, kmod), init
   (runit), networking (iproute2, dhcpcd, openssh), the kernel and initramfs
   (linux, dracut), the bootloader (grub, efibootmgr), the build toolchain
   (cmake, ninja, meson), and salt itself. After this stage the system can
   build and install its own packages.

4. desktop
   The LXQt edition (DISTRO.md section 15): the X11 display stack
   (mesa, llvm, xorg-server, openbox), Qt6, fonts and 2D libraries, the LXQt
   component stack, SDDM as the login manager, and the prebuilt Helium browser.

Network policy

Network access is allowed only while salt fetches and hash-verifies sources.
The base and desktop stages export SALT_NO_NETWORK=1 so the build phase runs
with networking denied, matching DISTRO.md section 13.

Running the build

Build the package set and assemble a sysroot:

  ARCH=x86_64  OUT=/var/tmp/saltos-build  sh os/bootstrap/bootstrap.sh
  ARCH=aarch64 OUT=/var/tmp/saltos-build  sh os/bootstrap/bootstrap.sh

Environment variables:
  ARCH   x86_64 | aarch64 (arm64/amd64 are normalized)
  OUT    work directory root (default /var/tmp/saltos-build)
  JOBS   build parallelism (default nproc)
  SALT   path to the salt binary (default: salt on PATH)

Built .grain files land in $OUT/$ARCH/packages and per-package logs in
$OUT/$ARCH/logs.

Assembling the rootfs

After the packages are built, populate a clean rootfs, install the runit
service tree, write fstab, and seed /etc:

  ARCH=x86_64 OUT=/var/tmp/saltos-build ROOTFS=/var/tmp/saltos-build/x86_64/rootfs \
    sh os/bootstrap/stage-rootfs.sh

This installs the base and desktop packages with salt install --root, copies
os/runit/sv into /etc/runit/sv, enables the default services by symlink into
/etc/runit/runsvdir/current, writes a Btrfs subvolume fstab
(@ @home @var @log @snapshots), and seeds hostname, hosts, os-release,
passwd/group, shells, and /etc/salt/repo.conf.

The resulting rootfs is consumed by os/iso (image assembly) and os/installer
(disk install). Bootloader deployment entries and the Btrfs subvolume creation
are handled at install time by the installer's custom module.
